You know, there's no consequences.

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:21.060
Um, the Dionysian is linked to the dance.

00:18:21.960 --> 00:18:32.700
Well, and so the style of this book must be the most danceable out of any, almost any of his works then with the, with the aphorism, with the quickness with which he attacks these.

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:38.760
I mean, he talks about it towards the end, I think of book five about sort of justifying the style a bit.

00:18:38.760 --> 00:18:50.140
Um, but it's, you know, that it's not, it's not lacking something because he's quickly moving between different conceptual terrain that that's actually something to try to cultivate.

00:18:50.140 --> 00:18:52.880
It's the positive quality that he's, yeah, exactly.

00:18:53.020 --> 00:18:53.420
Exactly.

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:54.860
So it's not a scholarly book.

00:18:54.860 --> 00:18:58.140
Like he clearly doesn't think of himself as a scholar, right?

00:18:58.160 --> 00:19:03.120
Like, and honestly, this is how the style book that I have been not writing for a decade.

00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:05.960
Um, like that's how I think of the style book.

00:19:05.960 --> 00:19:13.360
Like, I mean, it's, it's scholarly relative to, you know, most fucking New York Times bestseller things, but it's not a scholar.

00:19:13.460 --> 00:19:14.360
It's not scholar.

00:19:14.440 --> 00:19:17.120
I mean, you guys have read some of, some of the chunks of that.

00:19:17.240 --> 00:19:24.960
It's not scholarly in the sense of like making some sustained argument or investigation of documents or anything like that.

00:19:24.960 --> 00:19:29.880
It's just like vignettes of thoughts, you know?

00:19:30.340 --> 00:19:32.340
So that's how I very much think of that.

00:19:32.340 --> 00:19:36.860
I mean, I don't think of it in terms of dancing per se, but I do think of it as like, as light.

00:19:36.940 --> 00:19:40.260
In other words, I'm intentionally not sustaining an argument.

00:19:40.440 --> 00:19:43.060
It's not because I forgot that we were supposed to do that.

00:19:44.100 --> 00:19:44.460
Yeah.

00:19:48.840 --> 00:20:08.840
Back when I was working on the, the book project or the article or whatever, which Nathaniel and I did a couple, um, like collaborative sessions on, like, I feel like there's just, especially as a, a newcomer in the field, I feel like there's a lot of pressure to adhere to at least some version of, of scholarly traditionalism.

00:20:08.840 --> 00:20:14.880
But, but the, our field tends to encourage experimentation, at least in certain pockets.

00:20:14.880 --> 00:20:15.480
That's right.

00:20:15.700 --> 00:20:25.980
You know, so it's, it's difficult for me to embrace that transdisciplinary experimentation while at the same time feeling like, let me get something on the table.

00:20:25.980 --> 00:20:28.700
That's digestible to status quo.

00:20:29.020 --> 00:20:30.180
I mean, you're, you're right.

00:20:30.280 --> 00:20:33.100
And, and it's a, it's a time of career thing.

00:20:33.160 --> 00:20:40.720
Like I, when I, I mean, it was like four years ago for me when I hit upon the idea, I think I actually feel like it was Nathaniel's idea.

00:20:40.840 --> 00:20:41.480
I can't remember.

00:20:42.020 --> 00:20:47.220
But like there was, but there was a point where it was like, why do you have to write chapters?

00:20:47.220 --> 00:20:59.260
And it was, it was like, I had literally not had that thought before and chapters in the sense of like a 20, 20 to 25 page sort of sustained.

00:20:59.340 --> 00:21:05.000
And it's like, oh, I could just write six to 10 page, you know, vignettes.

00:21:05.420 --> 00:21:11.920
And that was incredibly, I was like, wow, that works so much better for, you know, everything that I want to do.

00:21:11.920 --> 00:21:21.560
And, but I mean, and like, I'm a relatively smart guy, but that thought had just never occurred to me because I was so, I mean, I was so, I had so cultivated the essay, right?

00:21:21.620 --> 00:21:27.720
Well, essay in the academic sense, not essay in the historical sense, right?

00:21:28.660 --> 00:21:41.140
And so, you know, that, that was, that was hugely liberating because it was like, oh my God, there's a fucking genre here that, and it's not like it's, I mean, it's not like it's sort of ludic.

00:21:41.400 --> 00:21:52.160
I don't think, you know, I think that it's just a different kind of rigor, but it's one that, you know, when, what, how many scholarly, how many books by people in our field have structures like that?

00:21:53.160 --> 00:21:56.000
Like, not that I can think of.

00:21:56.120 --> 00:22:00.000
I mean, I, I, maybe, maybe there is one or two, but I don't know.

00:22:00.060 --> 00:22:04.180
And it's not by the theory folks, you know?

00:22:04.240 --> 00:22:05.180
No, and I mean, you're right.

00:22:05.240 --> 00:22:11.100
It's totally a career thing because there's just, I mean, Nate, you doing something like that, there's an incredible risk to it.

00:22:11.100 --> 00:22:16.880
That if what you do isn't recognizable to someone else, then you're messing with the possibility of tenure, right?

00:22:16.980 --> 00:22:22.420
Whereas, like, John can do this, and even if nobody gives a shit, his job isn't threatened.

00:22:22.560 --> 00:22:24.200
Right, my job's not in jeopardy, right.

00:22:24.460 --> 00:22:29.940
So, like, yeah, your first book, just do your book and get the contract and get that fucking thing out there.

00:22:30.060 --> 00:22:34.800
Then you can, then you can experiment with other things because it doesn't matter after that.

00:22:36.180 --> 00:22:36.960
And, right.

00:22:37.440 --> 00:22:38.840
I mean, that really is, like, in some ways.

00:22:39.060 --> 00:22:40.300
That's the point, that's the point of tenure, right?

00:22:40.380 --> 00:22:42.440
Like, is, is precisely, like, use tenure.

00:22:42.900 --> 00:22:50.540
I mean, I'm going to spin that the other direction is that, you know, what it actually does is facilitate something far more interesting to happen.

00:22:50.540 --> 00:23:05.540
And not, not that it doesn't, I mean, it doesn't matter in the best of all possible ways and that you're not straightjacketed by, you know, that fear of, of not getting tenure of, by, by the form of the four or five chapter book, whatever it is.

00:23:06.320 --> 00:23:20.040
That, that, that it can open up lines of thinking that weren't otherwise available because, I mean, like, to go back to your style book, John, it's not like any of those, any of those vignettes are not recognizable as scholarly intellectual arguments.

00:23:20.040 --> 00:23:43.260
Every one of them is, is that, but the major advantage of it is that you're able to, and I think, you know, like, The Logic of Sense and A Thousand Plateaus is that you're able to come at a, a, a relatively narrow set of questions from, like, three or four times the number of angles that you would otherwise be afforded to it.

00:23:43.260 --> 00:23:48.440
And they can, they don't have to be all cut from the exact same sort of theoretical fabric.

00:23:48.440 --> 00:23:48.620
That's right.

00:23:48.720 --> 00:23:50.340
They don't have to line up perfectly.

00:23:50.540 --> 00:23:50.960
Right, right.

00:23:51.080 --> 00:24:02.000
And, and, you know, if there was one thing that I've learned from Deleuze and Nietzsche is the nuanced sense producing power of what we would often call paradox.

00:24:03.400 --> 00:24:16.400
And do you like, you know, actually finding intersecting lines rather than, you know, like coherent subordinate lines can just provide so much more precision.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:31.180
But I, but I, but I do, but I still, I mean, I, I hear you like there is, I mean, I remember that phase of my career where it was like, you know, I think I had more of an experimental sensibility when I was in grad school and it kind of got.

00:24:32.620 --> 00:24:44.600
Not intentionally, but it kind of just got trained out of me because I spent so much time trying to learn how to write an academic article and then an academic book.

00:24:44.800 --> 00:24:47.360
And so I just lost that.

00:24:47.940 --> 00:24:50.880
I mean, I go back and read some of the stuff that I wrote in graduate school.

00:24:51.020 --> 00:24:57.560
If, or if I think back about them, like they were some weird experimental things, you know?

00:24:58.340 --> 00:24:58.660
Yeah.

00:24:58.860 --> 00:24:59.220
Structural.

00:24:59.220 --> 00:25:00.900
Well, like you're writing the virus thing.

00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:02.200
Right, exactly.

00:25:02.360 --> 00:25:03.800
That's an example, you know?

00:25:04.240 --> 00:25:05.540
But you didn't do that in graduate school.

00:25:05.980 --> 00:25:06.980
That's super, but it's super weird.

00:25:07.620 --> 00:25:08.260
Yeah, I did.

00:25:08.660 --> 00:25:09.320
I think I did.

00:25:09.540 --> 00:25:09.920
Didn't I?

00:25:10.460 --> 00:25:12.020
You did that for a theory conference, I thought.

00:25:12.920 --> 00:25:20.760
No, but I think I took it, I took from a something, a chunk of something that I had written in graduate school and then, you know, refashioned it.

00:25:20.760 --> 00:25:21.700
Ah, fascinating.

00:25:21.840 --> 00:25:21.960
Right.

00:25:21.980 --> 00:25:27.360
Well, that kind of structural or stylistic experimentation, that's what seems to be rare.

00:25:27.540 --> 00:25:32.640
I feel like with content, our field is like, hey, let's talk about anything that we want at this point.

00:25:33.040 --> 00:25:36.920
Like we've opened the floodgates in terms of talking about different content.

00:25:36.920 --> 00:25:47.740
I think there's some, a little bit of leeway in terms of conceptual experimentation, like the fact that we have a theory wing of the field.

00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:51.980
The fact that Diane Davis can have a career writing those sorts of weird texts.

00:25:52.560 --> 00:26:00.320
But the kinds of experimentation that she did in breaking up a totality versus the rest of the field.

00:26:00.660 --> 00:26:01.580
Right, that's right.

00:26:01.680 --> 00:26:04.720
Like in terms of, stylistically, it's pretty homogenous.

00:26:04.980 --> 00:26:05.160
Yeah.

00:26:05.420 --> 00:26:05.780
Still.

00:26:06.780 --> 00:26:07.560
It feels like.

00:26:07.920 --> 00:26:08.500
But I don't know.

00:26:08.580 --> 00:26:13.160
I don't think you have to be structurally innovative to come up with an experiment.

00:26:13.340 --> 00:26:18.240
Like you can be, you can be experimental just in syntax in a formal essay.

00:26:18.260 --> 00:26:18.620
For sure.

00:26:18.840 --> 00:26:19.360
As well.

00:26:19.460 --> 00:26:21.760
Like there's all different types of experimentation.

00:26:22.260 --> 00:26:22.580
For sure.

00:26:22.580 --> 00:26:29.000
In fact, like I feel like something like Derrida's, glaw, like with the two sides, like to me, that just annoys me.

00:26:29.800 --> 00:26:30.020
Yeah.

00:26:30.020 --> 00:26:30.260
I don't know.

00:26:30.260 --> 00:26:31.560
I'm just like, give me one thing.

00:26:31.680 --> 00:26:32.800
It's too performance art.

00:26:32.800 --> 00:26:34.240
It's too like, look at me.

00:26:34.420 --> 00:26:35.500
I'm experimenting.

00:26:35.980 --> 00:26:36.040
Yeah.

00:26:36.060 --> 00:26:37.700
So, I mean, I agree with that.

00:26:37.780 --> 00:26:49.380
Like I've, that's why I've always liked, you know, like Hollywood movies that are smart as opposed to art films who scream, I'm smart, think about me.

00:26:51.240 --> 00:26:53.740
So, yeah, I mean, and that's a taste preference.

00:26:53.860 --> 00:26:54.960
I share that with you.

00:26:55.920 --> 00:27:06.340
Nonetheless, it would be cool to write something in the style of The Gay Science or something more aphoristic and have it published under the umbrella of like in our field.

00:27:06.460 --> 00:27:10.640
Something that, you know, got some momentum in our field that was written this way.

00:27:10.840 --> 00:27:11.040
Yeah.

00:27:11.460 --> 00:27:12.820
I mean, we've talked about this before.

00:27:13.100 --> 00:27:15.160
You can't even really, you can't write like Deleuze.

00:27:15.300 --> 00:27:19.280
You can't write like Derrida necessarily and get published easily.

00:27:19.600 --> 00:27:19.880
Yeah.

00:27:19.920 --> 00:27:20.380
We'll see.

00:27:20.480 --> 00:27:21.620
I mean, that's, that's the gambit.

00:27:21.720 --> 00:27:23.520
Well, I don't, somebody needs to pave the way.

00:27:23.600 --> 00:27:28.080
Somebody, I mean, if you get published with that book, maybe that would sort of be, maybe you'd be a trendsetter.

00:27:28.080 --> 00:27:30.840
Because I think you were that with the post-humanism as well.

00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:31.500
Yeah, yeah.

00:27:31.620 --> 00:27:35.500
At least with the, with the sort of historical work that I've been doing.

00:27:35.600 --> 00:27:37.040
You were the, I think the first person to use the term.

00:27:37.040 --> 00:27:37.840
I think we were the first.

00:27:37.860 --> 00:27:38.780
I think we were the first.

00:27:38.780 --> 00:27:38.900
You and Debbie.

00:27:38.900 --> 00:27:39.540
I think me and Debbie.

00:27:39.640 --> 00:27:39.800
Yeah.

00:27:39.840 --> 00:27:50.760
I think that thing that we did back in, I wish that I'd, I wish I'd hung on to that term in, in, in the invention book rather than post, rather than going to post-modernism.

00:27:51.180 --> 00:27:57.160
Because that was like the last death throw of post-modern, like nobody uses the word post-modernism anymore, you know.

00:27:57.520 --> 00:28:00.560
Was that a, that was a choice to, to commit to post-modernism?

00:28:00.620 --> 00:28:01.540
Because you could have gone.

00:28:01.680 --> 00:28:02.220
I could have.

00:28:02.340 --> 00:28:03.940
It's just at the time, there's still.

00:28:04.200 --> 00:28:04.880
Would have taken more work.

00:28:05.120 --> 00:28:09.660
Yeah, it was, and post-humanism wasn't a, wasn't really a word that circulated.

00:28:09.660 --> 00:28:17.900
I mean, when Debbie and I used it at that point, there was literally like two things in print that used the word post-humanism, you know, like.

00:28:18.140 --> 00:28:19.320
So there would have been no reference.

00:28:19.320 --> 00:28:20.060
There was nothing.

00:28:20.220 --> 00:28:22.780
Nobody had any idea what you meant about post-humanism.

00:28:22.880 --> 00:28:24.100
Carrie Wolfe had written his book.

00:28:24.240 --> 00:28:27.040
This is, Catherine Hales had written her book.

00:28:27.040 --> 00:28:31.820
The becoming whatever, why, how have we become post-human or something like that.

00:28:32.140 --> 00:28:32.920
So that was Catherine Hales.

00:28:32.960 --> 00:28:38.000
And she's totally lit person, you know, lit and science, science studies-y person.

00:28:38.220 --> 00:28:40.620
And then there was one other, I can't even remember what it was.

00:28:40.660 --> 00:28:41.660
There's one other thing.

00:28:41.720 --> 00:28:44.740
But that's why, that's where we pulled that term from.

00:28:45.260 --> 00:28:47.680
And, because it was a sort of science studies-y.

00:28:47.920 --> 00:28:50.300
But now it's ubiquitous, right?

00:28:50.300 --> 00:28:56.900
Well, now it's the point of departure as opposed to post-modernism.

00:28:56.960 --> 00:28:57.260
That's right.

00:28:57.260 --> 00:29:00.960
Now you have to, I mean, at least in rhetorical theory, you have to react to post-humanism.

00:29:00.960 --> 00:29:01.420
That's right.

00:29:01.660 --> 00:29:02.560
Or new materialism.

00:29:02.640 --> 00:29:03.880
New materialism or whatever.

00:29:04.060 --> 00:29:04.540
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:29:04.660 --> 00:29:06.000
No, that's totally right.

00:29:06.360 --> 00:29:06.560
Yeah.

00:29:06.840 --> 00:29:12.800
And post-modernism is just, I mean, who even uses the word anymore, you know?

00:29:13.880 --> 00:29:14.580
Nobody, really.

00:29:14.840 --> 00:29:15.040
Yeah.

00:29:15.280 --> 00:29:19.600
But should we tie, I mean, should we, should we, Nietzsche as a post-humanist?

00:29:20.020 --> 00:29:22.680
Have people really, I mean, I think Debbie's done a bit with that.

00:29:22.680 --> 00:29:34.400
Yeah, I teach it, I mean, I teach him as the, I mean, like, my undergrad class, yeah, my undergrad class, it was like, here's humanism, and we do the, we do some renaissance humanism.

00:29:34.400 --> 00:29:43.640
Pico de la Mirandola's Oration on the Dignity of Man, and that's great, because it really, concretely in five pages, teaches you humanism.

00:29:43.760 --> 00:29:47.660
It's about freedom and choice, you know, it's totally, like, liberal humanism.

00:29:48.520 --> 00:29:48.920
Right.

00:29:49.020 --> 00:29:56.980
And then I teach that in conjunction with Nietzsche, where he, you know, the beginning of Truth and Lies, where it's just like, oh, yeah, learning stuff is really so cool.

00:29:58.340 --> 00:30:05.660
And I just teach it as anti-human, I mean, I'm not trying to nuance it for them at all, I just teach this as humanism, anti-humanism, you know?

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:13.080
And then I teach that with Althusser as well, so Althusser will give the Marxist anti-humanist version.

00:30:13.760 --> 00:30:15.560
That sounds like a good class, man.

00:30:15.920 --> 00:30:16.780
I should be a teacher.

00:30:21.260 --> 00:30:25.200
It does feel like Nietzsche's post-humanism is unique.

00:30:25.380 --> 00:30:28.580
I mean, insofar as his philosophy can be categorized that way.

00:30:28.580 --> 00:30:38.400
Well, look, I mean, I, the, for me, the reason why I have all these years stayed on the Nietzsche train,

00:30:38.600 --> 00:30:44.300
I mean, they're, you know, other than that it's, like, sort of built into my soul at this point,

00:30:44.360 --> 00:30:51.300
but, like, is, is entirely that, like, over, the overcoming of the human is the project.

00:30:51.560 --> 00:30:51.960
That's it.

00:30:52.100 --> 00:30:53.060
That's the project.

00:30:53.300 --> 00:30:53.560
Of the human.

00:30:54.560 --> 00:30:55.000
Yes.

00:30:55.100 --> 00:30:56.880
The overcoming of the human is the project.

00:30:57.100 --> 00:31:05.980
And so, now, what that means is, is up for grabs, but he's, he's the first person to say, like,

00:31:06.060 --> 00:31:10.380
here's the point of, here's the point of thinking, to overcome the human, right?

00:31:11.460 --> 00:31:15.740
Here's the goal, here's what should be the goal of every life, to overcome the human.

00:31:16.600 --> 00:31:22.300
You know, I mean, it's just so straightforward, and so you can't, I mean, I can't think of

00:31:22.300 --> 00:31:27.280
another thinker in the 19th century who saw overcoming the human as the goal.

00:31:27.560 --> 00:31:34.000
And that, I mean, that's not, it's not, he doesn't mean, like, necessarily the destruction

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:35.580
of, of human being.

00:31:36.100 --> 00:31:36.500
Right.

00:31:36.600 --> 00:31:38.340
That's an important, that's right.

00:31:38.420 --> 00:31:38.580
I mean.

00:31:38.580 --> 00:31:39.320
It's not genocide.

00:31:39.500 --> 00:31:39.700
Yeah.

00:31:40.600 --> 00:31:41.000
Right.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:45.240
I mean, if you could specify it, though, like, it would be some version of overcoming

00:31:45.240 --> 00:31:45.760
resentment.

00:31:46.340 --> 00:31:46.560
Right.

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:48.700
But to me, the, the term would be subjectivity.

00:31:48.800 --> 00:31:50.860
Like, it's, it's a little more limited.

00:31:51.020 --> 00:31:54.660
Like, there's a version of human being that is driven by subjectivity.

00:31:54.760 --> 00:31:54.980
Right.

00:31:55.100 --> 00:31:56.560
And that's everybody, unfortunately.

00:31:57.060 --> 00:32:02.220
But that particular mobilization of the way that we relate to ourselves and to the world,

00:32:02.320 --> 00:32:06.220
that is what's become parasitic and, and problematic.

00:32:06.220 --> 00:32:09.960
This is, think of Foucault, the end of the, end of the order of things.

00:32:10.200 --> 00:32:13.360
If, if you haven't read, if you haven't read that, you totally should.

00:32:13.420 --> 00:32:20.060
But it's about man as being a face on the sand of recent invention or humanity.

00:32:20.060 --> 00:32:23.180
And like, that, that face is going to get washed away.

00:32:23.300 --> 00:32:27.700
And it's exactly, it's saying exactly what you are, which is, this is not about destroying

00:32:27.700 --> 00:32:28.460
bodies.

00:32:28.820 --> 00:32:29.300
Right.

00:32:29.340 --> 00:32:36.600
It's about creating different kinds of sensibilities, but it's also not void of bodies

00:32:36.600 --> 00:32:37.060
either.

00:32:37.340 --> 00:32:37.860
Right.

00:32:37.860 --> 00:32:39.900
It's not, it's not an idea.

00:32:39.900 --> 00:32:43.820
It's not, you know, so humanism, isn't just a series of ideas.

00:32:43.820 --> 00:32:46.960
They are in core, you know, incorporated ideas.

00:32:47.100 --> 00:32:51.360
They are ways of life that are, that are material and corporeal as well.

00:32:51.940 --> 00:32:56.160
So that's the hard thing is you don't want to just end up on the side of like the idealists

00:32:56.160 --> 00:32:58.480
and say like, Hey, we just want to change people's minds.

00:33:00.160 --> 00:33:02.440
It's like, no, we want to change their bodies too.

00:33:02.440 --> 00:33:02.720
Right.

00:33:02.720 --> 00:33:07.280
Like that's part of the, part of the project of the, the people who call themselves transhumanists,

00:33:07.280 --> 00:33:07.820
for instance.

00:33:07.820 --> 00:33:08.220
Right.

00:33:08.220 --> 00:33:13.540
Like, or, or cyborgs now, like there's tons of these folks who are doing weird shit with

00:33:13.540 --> 00:33:17.760
their bodies and brains and hooking technology up into them.

00:33:17.760 --> 00:33:20.640
And then to me, that's, that's of a piece, right?

00:33:20.640 --> 00:33:26.100
It's of a piece with other kinds of experiments that are about sort of producing a mode of response

00:33:26.100 --> 00:33:28.880
